  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>

        <div rend="parallel">
          <p xml:id="AN140.1-kilavi">iyaṟkkaip puṇarcci <app><lem>puṇarntu</lem><rdg wit="#C3">om.</rdg></app> nīṅkun talaimakaṉ pāṅkaṟku <app><lem>uraittaitu</lem><rdg wit="#NL #C3 #C5 #G1 #G2">colliyatu</rdg></app>.</p>
          <p xml:lang="en">What HE who left after having consumed the natural union said to [his] companion.</p>
        </div>
        <div rend="parallel">
            <lg xml:id="AN140.1">
              <l>peruṅkaṭal vēṭṭattuc ciṟukuṭip paratava</l>
              <l>riruṅkaḻic ceṟu<supplied>vi</supplied> ṉuḻātu ceyta</l>
              <l>veṇka luppiṉ koḷḷai cāṟṟi</l>
              <l>yeṉṟūḻ viṭara kuṉṟam pōkun</l>
              <l>tataraḻikō lumaṇar kātaṉ maṭamakaḷ</l>
              <l>cilkō lelvaḷai teḷirppa vīci</l>
              <l>nelli ṉērē veṇka luppeṉac</l>
              <l>cēri vilaimāṟu kūṟaliṉ maṉaiya</l>
              <l>viḷiyaṟi ñamali kuraippa verīiya</l>
              <l>matarkayaṉ malaippi ṉaṉṉa kaṇṇemak<anchor n="1"/></l>
              <l>ki<del>n</del><supplied>taimu</supplied>yal puṉava<supplied>ṉ</supplied> pukainiḻaṟ kaṭukku</l>
              <l>māmū taḷḷa laḻuntiya cākāṭ</l>
              <l>ṭevvan tīra vāṅkun tantai</l>
              <l>naiyūṇ pakaṭṭiṉ varunti</l>
              <l>veyya vuyirkku nōyā kiṉṟē.</l>
            </lg>
            <lg xml:lang="en">
                <l>When the beloved daughter of the salt-merchants with crushed, ruined staffs, (5)</l>
                <l>who go through the hills cleft by the sun,</l>
                <l>announcing the price for the salt in white lumps,</l>
                <l>made without ploughing the field in the dark backwaters</l>
                <l>by the fishermen in [their] small hamlets, on a search in the great sea, (1-4)</l>
                <l>flings [her arms about] so that the few beautiful bright bangles sound, (6)</l>
                <l>[and] proclaims the exchange for a price in the quarter: (8a-c)</l>
                <l>“salt in white lumps for equal rice!”, (7)</l>
                <l>[her] eyes, like [two] proud Kayal fish facing [each other], (10)</l>
                <l>frightened, when the sound-discerning dogs of the house bark, (8d-9)</l>
                <l>– they became an agony to us, who sigh hotly, (15)</l>
                <l>suffering like the bull with inferior food (14)</l>
                <l>of [her] father that drags, to end the trouble, (13)</l>
                <l>the cart that sank into the dark old mire, (12)</l>
                <l>resembling the haze of smoke from the farmer toiling on the dry-fields. (11)</l>
            </lg>
        </div>
    </body>
  </text>

